import pandas as pd
import collections
import numpy as np

def transform_data(df_history: pd.DataFrame) -> pd.DataFrame:
    # Work on a copy and keep only needed columns if present
    base_cols = [c for c in ["date", "symbol", "close"] if c in df_history.columns]
    df = df_history[base_cols].copy()

    # Normalize date to string YYYY-MM-DD
    df["date"] = pd.to_datetime(df["date"]).dt.strftime("%Y-%m-%d")

    # Sort for proper rolling computation
    df = df.sort_values(["symbol", "date"])

    # Ensure we have a clean, simple index to avoid alignment issues
    df = df.reset_index(drop=True)

    # Compute rolling means using transform to preserve index alignment
    df["ma_20"] = (
        df.groupby("symbol")["close"]
          .transform(lambda s: s.rolling(window=20, min_periods=1).mean())
    )
    df["ma_60"] = (
        df.groupby("symbol")["close"]
          .transform(lambda s: s.rolling(window=60, min_periods=1).mean())
    )

    # Reshape to long format for the moving averages
    df_long = df.melt(
        id_vars=["date", "symbol", "close"],
        value_vars=["ma_20", "ma_60"],
        var_name="ma_window",
        value_name="value",
    )

    # Map ma_window to numeric window size (20 or 60)
    window_map = {"ma_20": 20, "ma_60": 60}
    df_long["ma_window"] = df_long["ma_window"].map(window_map).astype(int)

    # Final tidy output
    transformed_df = df_long[["date", "symbol", "close", "value", "ma_window"]].reset_index(drop=True)
    return transformed_df
